nodes.title: Refiner Steps
widgets_values:
To change the % of steps performed by the Base SDXL model and the Refiner SDXL model, modify the value "refiner_start".

Example:

Refiner_start = 0.75 

This means 75% steps done by the Base, 25% steps done by the Refiner.


If you don't want the SDXL Refiner model to perform any step (useful when you use a fine-tuned SDXL Base model), set the "refiner_start" to 1.

nodes.title: MASK to SEGS
widgets_values:
*combined: if disabled, the mask will include any content within the boundaries of the SEGS, even if it has not been specified via GroundingDINO.

*crop_factor: multiplication factor for the size of the segment(SEGS)/boundary box(BBOX). It defines how much of the area surrounding the SEGS/BBOX should be considered during the detail recovery process. If this value is small, the restoration may not work well because the surrounding context cannot be known.

*bbox_fill: if enabled, the maks will include the content of the BBOX surrounding the SEGS.

*drop_size: any SEGS/BBOX smaller than this value will be ignored. It works in the opposite way of a guide_size value.

nodes.title: Negative Prompt
widgets_values:
When you generate an image you are actually generating two images, one for the positive, and one for the negative. If you set your CFG to 0 it will not use your positive prompt at all and you will see what image you are generating with the negative prompt.

The CFG is then determining how much to push your positive image away from the image you generated with the negative prompt.

If your negative prompt has "bad arm" it will generate a negative image with some form of arms, the CFG will then push your positive image away from anything resembling arms all together, making it difficult to generate "good arms".

it's much more useful to generate the opposite of what you want using the negative prompt. "bad arms" is not the negative of "good arms" because both of them contain arms, it is going to fight itself. Where "monochrome" is a valid negative if you want a vibrant, colorful image. Or "circles" is a valid negative if you want something geometric with sharp angles.

Again, use the negative you think you want with 0 CFG and then ask "is this the exact opposite of what I want, containing nothing at all that I want to keep?

From https://www.reddit.com/r/StableDiffusion/comments/18e9sio/negative_prompt_tips/

nodes.title: Prompt Builder
widgets_values:
The green nodes of this Prompt Builder compose the Positive Prompt, following a top to bottom order: Opening Modifiers + Type of Image + Image Subject + Image Style + Closing Modifiers.

Each green node offers a list of options, one per line, grouped according to their focus.

Each line is numbered from 0 to x. 
Line #0 is always empty. 

If you don't want a certain node to contribute to the Positive Prompt, be sure to select 0 for that node.

Once you have defined your prompt modifiers and styles, you probably only want to change the content of the Image Subject node.

--

The red nodes of this Prompt Builder compose the Negative Prompt.

Modify your Negative Prompt by choosing the desired option in the Negative String and Negative Embeddings switches below. 

Notice that negative embeddings are added at the end of the negative prompt. If you prefer a different order, you'll have to manually write your negative prompt.

nodes.title: High Fidelity vs Creativity
widgets_values:
To add detail to an image while keeping high fidelity, start with a "Denoise" value of 0.20, to fix high-fidelity.

Then, to add details, increase the noise "Strength" value to a small amount (e.g., 0.0030-0.0050).

Stronger noise = more details.

It's recommended you add microscopic increments (e.g., +/- 0.0005) to the noise "Strength" value.

nodes.title: System Prompt (Generic)
widgets_values:
You are a caption generator. I'll pass you a text that describes an image. You need to improve the description and rephrase it as a caption.

To perform this task, identify the key elements of the description and enrich each of them by adding many details.

For example, if the description contains the text "a yellow box sits on the table", you would identify and enrich "a yellow box", "sits", and "on the table".

Then, add some final words describing the high quality of the image.

To enrich the description and generate the caption, you must STRICTLY follow these rules:

1. You NEVER comment on the task, explain your choices, or write introductory text.

2. You NEVER output anything except your caption.

3. You NEVER end the caption with a period.

4. You NEVER exceed 60 words.

nodes.title: Size of the Small Faces (SEGS Filter range)
Face Detector
widgets_values:
*bbox_threshold: the confidence threshold for face recognition. If the Face Detector is identifying objects that are not faces as faces, increase this value. If the workflow is not picking up enough faces, decrease this value.

*bbox_dilation: by how much the node should expand the detected mask area.

*crop_factor: how many times the surrounding area should be included in the detail recovery process based on the detected mask area. If this value is small, the restoration may not work well because the surrounding context cannot be known. If it's too large, there will be very little upscaling done by the Detailer nodes and so less opportunity to improve the quality of the faces.

*drop_size: any segment(SEGS)/boundary box(BBOX) smaller than this value will be ignored. It works in the opposite way of a guide_size value.

nodes.title: Size of the Small Faces
widgets_values:
This "SEGS Filter range" node separates small face from large faces, detailing them in different ways.

Inside: anything within the min-max range.
Outside: anything beyond the min-max range.

If you see too many faces in the "Small Faces (SEGSPreview)" node, lower the "max_value".

Watch this YT tutorial for more information:
https://youtu.be/9ih35D2exMU

nodes.title: Force Inpaint
widgets_values:
When "force_inpaint" is disabled, any face larger than the value defined for "guide_size" will not be detailed.

This is useful if a face is already large and detailed enough and there's no need to redraw it. 

However, if your base model generates poorly detailed faces, it's probably a good idea to force inpaint all of them.

nodes.title: IPAdapter
widgets_values:
WARNING!! All IPAdapter models except "ip-adapter_sdxl.safesensors" require "clip_sd15.safesensors"

It's very confusing. Nothing I can do about it.

--

IPAdapter depends on CLIP Vision which only works with square images. The encoder resizes the image to 224x224px and crops it to the center!. It's not an IPAdapter thing, it's how the clip vision works. This means that if you use a portrait or landscape image and the main attention (eg: the face of a character) is not in the middle you'll likely get undesired results. Use square pictures as reference for more predictable results.

If you want to use landscape or portrait source images, you can add the "PrepImageForClipVision" node to this function.

--

For an explanation about the different weight_type options, and how to use the attn_mask option, watch this video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vqG1VXKteQg

nodes.title: Attention Mask for IPAdapter
widgets_values: Switch the node above to "Active" for IPAdapter to consider the mask you defined in the Uploader function.

nodes.title: Object Swapper
widgets_values:
*guide_size: any segment(SEGS)/boundary box(BBOX) larger than this value will be ignored. It works in the opposite way of a drop_size value. If the SEGS/BBOX is smaller than this value, the node will increase its resolution and attempt to recover details.

*guide_size_for: whether guide_size is used based on the size of the detected SEGS/BBOX or the size of the crop area that includes the face and is broadly cropped by crop_factor.

*max_size: the guide_size increases the scale so that the shorter side reaches the guide_size. For masks with elongated shapes, this can cause a significant scale up. The max_size limits the maximum size of one side.

*feather**: the thickness of the gradient used to compose the recovered details onto the original image, so that the boundaries are not visible.

*noise_mask: if enabled, denoising will not be applied outside the masked area, which can result in a safer generation with stronger denoising, but it may not always produce good results.

*force_inpaint**: force_inpaint will try to force regeneration even if it is smaller than guide_size. This function is useful when you simply want to change to another type of prompt other than the function to save details. However, in this case, upscale is forcibly fixed to 1.
    

Partially copied from: 
https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ltdrdata/ComfyUI-extension-tutorials/Main/ComfyUI-Impact-Pack/tutorial/advanced.md

nodes.title: SD1.5 model for Hands Detailer
widgets_values:
This Hands Detailer function uses a diffusion model based on Stable Diffusion 1.5 because no fine-tuned SDXL model for hands anatomy has been released, yet. 

Once one will be available, select it in the Load Checkpoint node and change the OpenPose ControlNet model to the SDXL version, too.


For more information on this function:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DoyqCjKdojY

nodes.title: Cycles
widgets_values:
The number of cycles defines how many passes the detailer must perform. Increase the value if you want more detailed hands.

The Detailer starts the first cycle with the denoise value indicated above and then progressively reduces/increases the noise according to the "target_denoise" setting in the "DenoiseSchedulerDetailerHookProvider" node, on the left.

nodes.title: Denoise for Inpainting w/ Mask
widgets_values: Keep the denoise value to 1 for outpainting.

nodes.title: Hand Detailer
widgets_values:
The Hand Detailer cannot fully redraw hands because we still don't have exceptional models that can do that.

The Hand Detailer, instead, will try improve the aspect of existing hands by using the anatomy of the hand as guidance.

The Hand Detailer uses the new Mesh Graphormer method and the Inpaint Depth Hand ControlNet model.

For more information: https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.17957

nodes.title: Prompt Enrichment (ChatGPT)
widgets_values:
You are a prompt generator for Dall-E. I'll pass you a text that describes an image and you need to improve it to generate a caption.

Identify the key elements of my text and enrich each of them by adding many details. Then, add some final words describing the high quality of the image.

For example, if I would pass the text "a yellow box sits on the table", you would identify and enrich "a yellow box", "sits", and "on the table".

To enrich the text I'll pass and generate the caption, you must STRICTLY follow these additional rules:

1. Do not comment on the task or write introductory text. For example, do not say things like "The image presents a yellow box sitting on a table..." or "In the image, a yellow box sits on a table...". Just describe the image with something like "a yellow box sits on a table..."

2. Do not output anything except the enriched paragraph describing the image as a caption.

3. Do not capitalize the first letter of the paragraph.

4. End the paragraph WITHOUT a period.

nodes.title: CCSR Upscaling Steps
widgets_values:
CCSR upscaling with the Gaussian Weights method (recommended) seems to yield the best out-of-the-box results at 6x and above.

For upscaling up to 4x, you can keep the "steps" value at 3 (the minimum) without observable quality degradation. 

For upscaling from 6x and above, a "steps" value of 20 is recommended.
